I think there's a general perception that Islam means a dull, grey,
humorless and artless world. Possibly there are fundamentalist Islamic
sects or groups that see it that way, but that's probably more because
they're fundamentalist kill-joys somewhere to the right of the
roundheads when it comes to colour, decoration and aesthetic concerns.

Whilst on holiday recently I spent an afternoon at the excellent
Gulbenkian Collection in Lisbon (and I'll add that IMO Lisbon is a top
notch destination if you're wanting to do something other than party
or lie around on a beach with luridly coloured cocktails with
umbrellas stuck in them).

The Gulbenkian is arranged thematically, with the various rooms
representing various eras and/or countries.

One of these rooms, a pretty large one, was a display of middle-
eastern arts and crafts  from the 15th to 17th centuries. You might
read &quot;middle-eastern&quot; as &quot;Islamic&quot; if you care.

I was astonished by the richness of the colours and designs on
display. Beautiful illuminated Quranic manuscripts from the 15th
century with vivid colors and exquisite illustrations. More surprising
in a way were the many examples of decorative objects from homes in
places like Persia (as it then was) and Syria. Wonderful panels of
richly coloured and patterned tiles, a decorative fireplace etc. Not
to mention some lovely pieces of jewellery and some beautifully
embroidered clothing.

It gave nothing away in terms of craftsmanship and richly coloured eye
candy to the nearby room of 16th and 17th chinese arts and crafts.
